dialogue: I’m all good.
I don’t know what you want me to say. I’m good. That’s basically it.
Well, she’s definitely high. The whole place stinks like weed.
Fuck yes, I’m high. High as a motherfucker. First thing I do in the morning is roll a blunt. And then I smoke at least three more throughout the day. You know why? Because that’s how I do shit.
I don’t care that you smoke weed. It’s just not right to smoke it in the house, when someone is sick.
Daddy doesn’t mind. Trust me, I’ve been smoking around him for all this time and he never had an issue. In fact, he likes the smell. Told me more than a few times.
It’s the smoke. The smoke, not the smell. The man is dying, just go outside.
Damn, it took you five minutes, five minutes, right? For you just to get in my shit. A second ago, it was how let’s just get along—
Shitty weed? Please. I get top shelf, not that dogshit you smoked all day long. Right? You think I forgot that?
That was high school. I’ve grown up quite a lot since then, unlike others.
Grown up, still a bitch.
What was that?
The food. The food that I made. Are you enjoying it?

Yes. I like the food you made. Thank you for making the food you made. The food you made tastes good. I have a parlay going and I’m on the final team, that’s why I am looking at my phone. I’m working.
You mean you are watching a game, that you bet on.
Uh huh. Bet on four. Won three. 10 bucks to make 270.
Do you think watching will change its outcome?
Thank you for the dinner.
Watch her not even wash her dis-
That’s funny. Christina is wearing pajama bottoms and a 2003 Tour shirt of The Dead.
Your shirt.
Do you want to put some clothes on and join us? Angel was just telling us about where he thinks things are.
Um. Sure.
How about some coffee?
Yes? Eventually, Rachel opens her door.

Here’s the thing. I get it that you don’t want to go into his room. Sure, I was there till four a.m. and Christina has basically been in there since. The help would be appreciated, but look, everyone deals with death their own way, and I am not going to tell you what to do. That’s between you, and him, and however you think you should run your life. But what I am going to ask you to do is not act like a teenager and sneak smoking in the bathroom. It’s not sneaking. The whole place reeks of it, and I’m not even asking for you to do it for him, even though he can’t speak for himself. I’m asking for me. I’m asking you to respect me, and my wishes, and while he’s alive and I’m here, to smoke outside. That’s it. Afterwards, this will be your place, you’re on the lease, and you will be free to do whatever you want and I will have no say. You want only rotten apples in the fridge, not my business. You want to do bong hits all day and all night, not my business. But for now, whenever you step outside to smoke, think “I’m respecting Katie”, and I’ll know that you are respecting me. Okay? Okay?
Sure.
I don’t want to hear it. Not in the mood.
Yes? Is there a problem?
Is there a problem? You tell me?
Please, don’t start. We smoked outside as you asked. Now we are back in my room, taking care of ourselves.

You don’t think it’s a bit weird? I mean, it’s kind of strange, no? Having a random person over to the house, now? At a time like this? You really think it’s right to have a stranger here when he may pass at any minute?
He’s not random. Benjy and I have been hanging out for a while now. Just because you don’t know him, doesn’t mean he’s a stranger. And daddy likes him. That’s what matters.
Okay. Rachel lingers for a moment.
Okay.
Not interested.
I haven’t said anything.
Not interested in whatever you want to say.
Well, I am trying to say—

Here’s the thing. We don’t need to say anything to each other. There’s nothing to be said, nothing I want to hear. You do what you need to while you are here, afterwards that will be it. We won’t have anything to do with each other. We can just stay out of each others way till then.
That’s not very practical, nor is that really what I think is right.
This isn’t about you.
That’s right, it’s not about either of us. It’s about our father.
Oh, our father? That’s funny.
Why?
Because you only call him “our father” when you want something from me. Usually, you say “my father”.
Don’t be ridiculous.
Fuck your apology. For real.
Nice. Nice. You slam the door when he’s dying next door. You’re a fucking spoiled bitch!
What the fuck are you doing? Are you—
You’ll do what? You’ll destroy me? You’re a fucking punk. That’s it. You are a cheap—
Christina. You need to do something about this bitch, ‘cause in about five seconds—
You’re not going to do shit. Bring it on! You’re a fucking coward. A leeching, broke ass, live at home —
Yeah, sorry for what?
For one thing, criticizing you about the apples being in there. I hadn’t known they were for dad. I’m sorry, I wish I did.
And that makes all the difference? The apples tells you all you need to know?
It was one thing. It was a thing, that I assumed incorrectly.
Anything else?
Sure.
From the beginning I’ve understood I was in your place.
That’s bullshit. This is your place too. You know it, I know it.
But you live here. You are on the lease.
That’s the second time you mentioned this lease shit. What is that? What are you trying to say?
And you brought it up too. Outside. What’s up with this?
Nothing. Just the facts. When he dies, this becomes your place.
Do you think that’s what I want? That I give a shit about the place?

C’mon, Rachel, of course you care about him. But this place is a good deal, let’s be truthful about it. No one has rent like this in this city. I mean just about. It doesn’t exist. This is good, I’m happy for you. I want you to have it.
Well then fuck it. I don’t want it. Now what?
Don’t be silly. Why would you leave?
Because then we are done with each other, and this shit is a wrap.
This doesn’t make any sense. Christina, can you explain what this is all about?
And father.
Well, duh. I know that. But he’s my dad too. That’s what I’m saying.
He’s my dad too. Just as much as he is both of yours.
But you also had another dad.
Who I never fucking knew. Who died when I was four fucking years old.
But he was still your father. And when he was, Vincent was ours.

Okay, here it is. This is what this is all about. I. Did. Not. Have. A. Father. Before him. What part of that do you not understand? He’s been daddy to me. That’s my dad, over there. In here. Fucking dying. That is my dad. That’s my dad.
I know, I know. I’m not saying he’s not.
Oh he loves me. I love you too little doggy. You’re just a great little big beast. Fucking slobbering little cute thing. Damn, that’s a good dog you got. Eats like a horse, I bet.
That’s right. You got it.

You should open earlier, you know that? What is this ten a.m. bullshit? I swear, this neighborhood is going to shit. I should open up my own blunt store, 24 hours, no bullshit, just here’s your shit and get the fuck out of here. Fucking wholesale. Ha, just play—
Rachel!

Wasn’t that yesterday? I mean, no offense, but for real, we know he’s dying. Like, we get it. You say you can’t say when, but then come here and tell us this is it every day. I’m not speaking for them, but it’s kind of wearing on me, y’know?
It’s a lot. It’s been a lot of “time to say goodbye”.
It was definitely yesterday.
And today.
I couldn’t help it. The dude is here every day saying he’s going to die. Bad enough as it is, but he’s dramatic as fuck.
I know, I know.
I’m high, so what do I know?
I don’t know. I’m just tired. But it’s true.
Good morning, your dad’s dying, may I have some coffee?
He could do that thing where the quarter disappears.
Oh yeah.
Yeah, what relationship is that?
Well. What do you want it to be?
No, you pick up the phone.
I don’t care that you are at lunch, if you don’t want to talk before school, this is what happens. Tracy, Tracy, listen to me. I need you to stop, and hear me...
-do not do that. Tracy, I am asking you to not-
Trac-
Are you sure you don’t want half, at least?
I don’t really know anything about writing those things.
Me neither.

...Vincent was proud to work for The Department of Citywide Administrative Services. After thirty-two years, he retired as a senior supervisor, beloved by his colleagues. Vincent will be remembered for his dedication to his family and friends, his welcoming spirit, warm wit, and an unwavering love for the Jets.
That’s it?
So far. And I know it all sounds so...dry. But I’m not sure how to sum up his life in just a few words.
Seems like a pretty good job so far. I’m not sure who reads those things anyway. I don’t. If you knew the person, you knew the person.
It’s more a record. Just to have. Like saying “this person existed”, in case anyone wants to know.
I’m gonna put my money that you could write anything and no one’s going to notice.
Married a couple crazy bitches, raised a few crazy bitches.
Thanks.
Ok, serious. Let’s see... Vincent... Vincent loves the Jets.
Yeah. Got that.

He loves to laugh at stupid shit. He likes old movies. He listens to records. He’d call in on news radio sometimes and get into it. He can get crazy mad, start yelling about things, then forget about what.
...”doesn’t give a fuck about a lot of things you shouldn’t”... Well, that’s true.
Everything I just said was true.
I know. And it’s more interesting than what I wrote, but in the end, it’s a list too.
I tried.
I think what he was saying is, we won’t really know who he was till after.
Yeah, kinda.

Well, like who they are right now. It’s not my business, but I hear you and Tracy going at it. But that’s just who she is right now, as a teenager. You know that. I think Pops was talking the whole thing, like all of it. All the different times, different people we can be. Y’know, for it all.
Yeah. That’s easy to forget. With Tracy. It feels like she will be like this forever.
I mean, she may be still spoiled when she gets older, but you know, a different spoiled.
I’m just playing.
Yes. I know.
I’m sorry I wasn’t here more. To help you. I know it was a lot.
It was fine. I liked it. But thanks.
And I hope you don’t leave this place.
Why?
Because I want to keep the apartment in the family.
I think dad wants to sit up.
Really? Are you sure?
I’ll get it.
Are you sure dad?
What’s up, Pops? It sure is good to see you back in your chair.
Pillow? I think—he wants his pillow for his back. It’s in my room. On my bed, against the wall.
Here you go daddy. Look at you. Back in charge. Just like that. Knew you weren’t down yet.
What do we do? I don’t think he’s supposed to eat anything.
Dad!
Daddy!
